{
  "topicId": "m7-t2",
  "title": "Talking About Daily Programs and Habits",
  "dialect": "fusha",
  "steps": [
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Introduction: Daily Routines and Habits"
        },
        "text": "In this lesson, you will learn how to discuss your daily schedule and recurring activities in Arabic. We'll start with essential vocabulary for routines and habits.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "برنامج يومي",
            "english": "Daily program / Daily schedule",
            "transliteration": "barnāmaj yawmī"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "عادة",
            "english": "Habit",
            "transliteration": "ādah"
          },
          {
            "arabic": "عادات يومية",
            "english": "Daily habits",
            "transliteration": "ādāt yawmiyyah"
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Verb: I wake up / I get up (أستيقظ)"
        },
        "text": "The verb 'أستيقظ' means 'I wake up' or 'I get up'. This is a common verb used when discussing the start of your day. It's in the present tense, first person singular.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "أستيقظُ",
            "english": "I wake up / I get up",
            "transliteration": "astayqithu",
            "diacriticalNotes": "The 'ض' (ḍād) sound is similar to a 'd' but deeper and more emphatic."
          },
          {
            "arabic": "أستيقظ مبكراً.",
            "english": "I wake up early.",
            "transliteration": "astayqithu mubakkiran."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "content",
      "content": {
        "title": {
          "english": "Verb: I eat (آكل)"
        },
        "text": "'آكل' means 'I eat'. This verb is fundamental for talking about meals throughout your day. Notice the long 'aa' sound at the beginning.",
        "examples": [
          {
            "arabic": "آكلُ",
            "english": "I eat",
            "transliteration": "aakulu",
            "diacriticalNotes": "The hamza on alif followed by another alif indicates a long 'aa' sound."
          },
          {
            "arabic": "آكل الفطور.",
            "english": "I eat breakfast.",
            "transliteration": "aakulu al-futur."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "practice-sentence",
      "sentence": {
        "arabic": "أستيقظ باكراً كل يوم.",
        "english": "I wake up early every day.",
        "transliteration": "astayqithu bakiran kulla yawm."
      },
      "context": "Using 'أستيقظ' to describe a daily routine."
    },
    {
      "type": "practice-sentence",
      "sentence": {
        "arabic": "عندي عادة أن آكل فطوراً صحياً.",
        "english": "I have a habit of eating a healthy breakfast.",
        "transliteration": "indī ādah an aakula futur an sahhiyy an."
      },
      "context": "Combining 'عادة' with 'آكل' to express a habit."
    },
